2019-08-14.text: wanting to inflict harm is a choice? Most people would cry when they bleed or at least be in pain, yet someone with mental health issues does it because they’re brain says they should or because they deserve it

something having a lasting effect on you. What baffles me most is that if mental health is a choice, then why is there treatment & medications for it? Science tends not to get things wrong. Cancer isn’t a choice, autism isn’t a choice but wanting to end your life is??

My BPD means I get confused easily, and I have a hard time understanding relationships. I don’t choose that. To me the world is black and white, but the reality is that it’s not. Trauma has made it that way for me. You can’t go through trauma without -
I’ve never chosen to think my neighbours are spies, or my medication somehow makes others ill... why would I choose to think like that?

With the most basic of things. For example a trip to the store turns into a journey because the crippling fear of somebody knowing something about you even though you’ve never met them overpowers rational thinking. I don’t choose to think like that -

I would like you to imagine you have been given a plate of bugs or something disgusting. You’re being told to eat said thing. Imagine the anxiety that would give you at having to put that in your mouth and chew. For people with anxiety, that is an everyday occurrence -

I was diagnosed with depression, anxiety & borderline personality disorder two years ago. I’m going to focus on BPD because believe it or not, I do not choose to have periods of manic emotions because somebody made me laugh.
